Firstly, for IPA I cannot address this:
>>How to manually complete or finalize the replica install given that all services are running and only sysrestore.state shows complete=False
Because even though it looks like it was the last step in the replica install, it probably wasn't. 
E.g., you have the installation called with
~~~
DEBUG ipa-replica-install was invoked with arguments [] and options: {'unattended': False, 'ip_addresses': None, 'domain_name': 'ipa.calix.local', 'servers': ['cpeg-ipareplica.ipa.calix.local'], 'realm_name': 'IPA.CALIX.LOCAL', 'host_name': None, 'p
rincipal': 'admin', 'hidden_replica': False, 'setup_adtrust': False, 'setup_ca': True, 'setup_kra': False, 'setup_dns': True, 'no_pkinit': False,
~~~
no_pkinit :false, means that the PKINIT setup still needs to run for the KDC, and I don't see the task being executed in the replica install logs.

So the installation script still has more steps to go. So I cannot really provide you with a 'workaround' in this scenario because we cannot attest
it will work *at all*.

One thing in addition that I can suggest, is to do a quick workaround for the directory server in 'pln' during the install which involves:

1. Modifying this file:
/usr/share/ipa/replica-prevent-time-skew.ldif

to contain:
~~~
dn: cn=config
changetype: modify
replace: nsslapd-ignore-time-skew
nsslapd-ignore-time-skew: on
~~~

And then attempt the installation. This should make 'nsslapd-ignore-time-skew' be set to on even after dirsrv restarts and it *should* work.
But *ideally* - these repl errors should be taken care of.

